occurrences.line_text: In which that manly person late did fade,
Where sleeping late she left her other knight.
There by his maister left, when late he far'd
Well could he him remember, sith of late
Awaiting passage, which him late did faile;
Sith late with him I batteil vaine would boste;
Late left beyond that Ydle lake, proceedes
To weet, whence all the wealth late shewd by mee,
And loue auowd to other Lady late,
Well knew they both his person, sith of late
And those two Sarazins confounded late,
Early and late it rong, at euening and at prime.
His wanton sports, being returned late
At last ripe age bad him surrender late
The wretched man gan then auise too late,
And that of Cambry king confirmed late,
By dew successe, and all their Nephewes late,
Till gentle Alma seeing it so late,
Some like wild Bores late rouzd out of the brakes;
The knight yet wrothfull for his late disgrace,
And shiuered ships, which had bene wrecked late,
That was the wanton Phoedria, which late
And yet through languour of her late sweet toyle,
And of the fairest late, now made the fowlest place.
That had an hog beene late, hight Grille by name,
Where through long watch, & late dayes weary toile,
Late foule dishonour and reprochfull spight,
My feeble brest of late, and launched this wound wyde.
Which the late world admyres for wondrous monime[n]ts.
Of his late puissaunce, his Image dead,
Then shall the Britons, late dismayd and weake,
Late King, now captiue, late Lord, now forlorne,
Late King, now captiue, late Lord, now forlorne,
Will not long misery late mercy make,
Late dayes ensample, which these eyes beheld,
In th'euening late old Glauce thither led
They came, as Merlin them directed late:
That in late yeares so faire a blossome bare,
Least afterwards it be too late to take thy flight.
And findeth dew effect or soone or late.
Who through late triall, on that wealthy Strond
Ne of thy late life memory is left,
The guilt I doe ascribe: deare wisedome bought too late.
Whom late in chace of beautie excellent
With some late perill, which he hardly past,
The want of his good Squire late left behind,
In their sterne brests, on him which late did driue
But that fierce foster, which late fled away,
Tho when that villain he auiz'd, which late
Of life, whom late their Ladies arrow ryu'd:
And euery one her answerd, that too late
After late chace of their embrewed game,
Her golden lockes, that late in tresses bright
Sad Amaranthus, made a flowre but late,
Pleasure, the daughter of Cupid and Psyche late.
From Stygian shores, where late it wandered;
His late miswandred wayes now to remeasure right.
Who when too late awaking, well they kent,
Where late he left the Beast, he ouercame,
But that accursed Hag, her hostesse late,
Late forth she sent, she backe returning spyde,
Which Florimell had left behind her late,
Sith late mischaunce had her compeld to chaunge
To fetch from sea, that ye at land lost late;
Then tooke he him yet trembling sith of late,
To tell of Satyrane, where I him left of late.
Is the late ruine of proud Marinell,
Like as the rest, late entrance deare besought;
Though nought beleu'd, & entrau[n]ce late did not refuse.
Like as Minerua, being late returnd
With his late fall, and fowle indignity,
And knightly worth, which he too late did try,
Her crased health, her late recourse to rest,
That floures so fresh at morne, and fades at euening late?
Of pardon for the strife, which late befell
But Paridell complaynd, that his late fight
Still when he mused on his late mischiefe,
Sith late he fled from his too earnest foe:
Where late his treasure he entombed had,
From Limbo lake him late escaped sure would say.
Nor ward to wait at morne and euening late,
Bold Britomart, as she had late forecast,
He glad of life, that lookt for death but late,
And put away remembrance of late teene;
More easie issew now, then entrance late
Where late she left the pensife Scudamore,
At last she came vnto the place, where late
Her body, late the prison of sad paine,
For praising loue, as I haue done of late,
Brought in that mask of loue which late was showen:
She old and crooked were, yet now of late,
Yet mindfull how he late by one was feld,
This knight too late his manhood and his might,
That as I late aduentured for your sake,
But Paridell that had too late a tryall
In which you safe I see, whom thousand late,
That so their liues might be prolonged late.
That well (me seemes) appeares, by that of late
But that he yet was sore of his late lucklesse fight.
Which Ferrau late from Braggadochio wonne,
Through grieuaunce of his late receiued wound,
Both in remembrance of his friends late harme,
Whose luckelesse riders late were ouerthrowen;
And that late weaker band of chalengers relieued.
She through his late disguizeme[n]t could him not descrie.
Nathelesse she full of wrath for that late stroke,
And wearie limmes recur'd after late vsage bad.
And loth to leaue her late betrothed make,
Where sorie Britomart had lost her late;
Thence she them brought toward the place, where late
Which to this gentle Squire did happen late.
That likewise late had lost her dearest loue;
After late weary toile, which she had tride
Like ghost late risen from his graue agryz'd,
He chaunst to come where those two Ladies late,
Through her late hurts, and through that haplesse wound,
Her person late in perill, did remaine,
Whome they had lost in Turneyment of late,
In that late Turney for the snowy maide;
And being brought in daunger, to relent too late.
To weet faire Britomart, them late had foyled
Through which this shield of loue I late haue wonne,
Bearing the shield which I had conquerd late,
But that same Ladie which me friended late
Rich Oranochy, though but knowen late;
For in the selfe same riuer, where he late
And balefull Oure, late staind with English blood:
It's late in death of daunger to aduize,
And all the ill, which chaunst to me of late,
That a proud Amazon did late defy
To whom she bore most feruent loue of late,
Ne would I it haue ween'd, had I not late it prieued.
In sort as ye haue heard the same of late.
Of a late wrong vppon a mortall foe;
His father Dolon had deuiz'd of late
Which late her folke had slaine, she bad the[m] forth to hold.
And her late vile reproch, though vaunted vaine,
Him to refresh, and her late wounds to heale:
Where righteous Artegall her late exyled;
And turne we to the noble Prince, where late
Well solast in that Souldans late delight,
After her Noble husbands late decesse;
Deliuer him his owne, ere yet too late,
The whole occasion of his late misfare,
Vntill late mischiefe did vppon me light,
I layd aside, and haue of late forbore,
And all such persons, as did late maintayne
Sir Artegall return'd from his late quest,
From his late conquest, which he gotten had.
Which ye haue had in your late enterprize.
Hauing late slaine her Seneschall in fight,
Of his late fall, a while he rested still:
Who comming forth yet full of late affray,
Nathelesse, sith ye so courteous seemed late,
Vpon the steed of her owne late dead knight:
By late ensample of that courteous deed,
And heare th'aduenture of her late mischaunce;
Of so long waies to him befallen late.
From that vile lozell, which her late offended,
Of all this land, late conquer'd by his sword
In saluage forrest I him lost of late,
Of that same Monster late, for lacke of heed,
Which Turpine had vnto her shewed late,
Not onely her excluded late at night,
Of their late woundes, the which the Blatant Beast
For his late villanies.
He of the Prince his life receiued late,
Backe to the place, where Turpine late he lore;
Of all his mischiefe, and late lucklesse smart;
Had for his food late gathered from the tree,
Whom late we left ryding vpon an Asse,
Fell into wretched woes, which she repented late.
By meanes his leg through his late luckelesse prise,
To rest my barcke, which hath bene beaten late
That all those Ladies, which thou sawest late,
Or to present her with their labours late;
Gan cry to them aloud, to helpe ere all too late.
As if he did from some late daunger fly,
But he, whose hart through feare was late fordonne,
Right well knew Coridon his owne late sheepe,
After a late forray, and slept full sound,
Hauing of late by diligent inquest,
But now by this, with noyse of late vprore,
He growen is so great and strong of late,
I, whether lately through her brightnesse blind,
Saying, that harlot she too lately knew,
I lately chaunst (Would I had neuer chaunst)
By that, which lately hapned, Vna saw,
I lately traueild, that vnwares I strayd
As with lamenting eyes him selfe did lately vew.
Sith his good steed is lately from him gone;
He lately heard that dying Lady grone,
And weetlesse eke of lately wrought despight,
Which in his land he lately did appease,
Was by Maximian lately led away,
Till they arriued, where they lately had
And eke those six, which lately with her fought,
Octa and Oza, whom he lately brake
Of whom he asked, whence he lately came,
To tell the same. I lately did depart
Who lately left the same, and tooke this way:
Where you him lately left, in Mars his bed;
Faire Psyche to him lately reconcyld,
Like to a ghost, that lately is reuiued
Which thou vpon thy selfe hast lately ta'ne?
And eke their lately bruzed parts to bring in plight.
And the wyde wound, which lately did dispart
And much the more, by that he lately wrought,
Herein, as thus. It lately so befell,
Hath lately caus'd to be proclaim'd each where
It was the same, which lately Florimel had lost.
That lately turneyd, had the wager wonne:
He in an open Turney lately held,
For lately he my loue hath fro me reft,
By Braggadochio lately was redeemed.
Which he had lately seene, that for his loue he chose.
He lately tooke, and sithence kept as thrall.
Whom (as ye lately mote remember well)
With Braggadochio, whom he lately met
Who hauing lately left that louely payre,
From deathes dore, at which he lately lay,
Was lately broken by some fortune ill;
From which he lately had through reskew fled:
Whom from her Seneschall he lately freed,
Since I him lately lost, vneath is to define.
So lewdly had abusde, as ye did lately heare.
Through many wounds, which lately he in fight
Which lately sought his Lord for to displease:
That was an oaken plant, which lately hee
Backe to the furrow which I lately left;
I lately left a furrow, one or twayne
Some vprore were like that, which lately she did vew.
But when his later spring gins to auale,
And well I wote, that of your later fight
And later times things more vnknowne shall show.
But other some by gift of later grace,
Least worse betide thee by some later chaunce.
But later ages pride, like corn-fed steed,
Thou that doest liue in later times, must wage
And named it Albion. But later day
Let later age that noble vse enuie,
Their of-spring hath embaste, and later glory shent.
The glory of the later world to spring,
Brayes out her latest breath, and vp her eyes doth seele.
Till he with old Latinus was constraind,
And with Latinus did the kingdome part.
At last in Latium he did arriue,
Till that Latona traueiling that way,
As when Latonaes daughter cruell kynde,
Latonaes childrens wrath, that all her issue wasted.
As they are wont vnto Latonaes sonne,
Holding a lattice still before his face,
Lauding and praysing his renowmed worth,
The which into an ample lauer fell,
Ay wont to laugh, when them I heard to cry,
Did seeme to laugh on me, and fauour mine intent.
Sometimes to doe him laugh, she would assay
To laugh at shaking of the leaues light,
The fields did laugh, the flowres did freshly spring,
Both foolish knights, I can but laugh at both,
At which they all gan laugh full merrily:
He lowdly gan to laugh, and thus to iest;
Thereat all Knights gan laugh, and Ladies lowre:
Then would he laugh aloud, and gather great delight.
And heauens laugh, & all the world shews ioyous cheare.
To laugh at me, and fauour my pretence,
Ladies can laugh at Ladies, Knights at Knights,
Did laugh at her, that many did deride,
Did laugh at those that did lament and plaine:
Withall she laughed, and she blusht withall,
(Thereat full hartely laughed Satyrane.)
He where he list goes loose, and laughes at me.
The more he laughes, and does her closely quip,
The laughing stocke of fortunes mockeries,
Full of disport, still laughing, loosely light,
Some as the Rubine, laughing sweetly red,
For both the boughes doe laughing blossomes beare,
To find them out. Mote I (then laughing sayd
Laughing on her, his false intent to shade,
Who mocketh all my paine, & laughs the more I mourn.
Sometimes she laught, that nigh her breth was gone,
Therewith she laught, and did her earnest end in iest.
Some song in sweet consort, some laught for ioy,
And therewith loudly laught: But nathemore
Ioue laught on Venus from his soueraigne see,
Laught at his foolish labour spent in waste;
And euer as Dissemblance laught on him,
Some laught for sport, some did for wonder shout,
Ne euer laught, ne once shew'd countenance glad;
And laught so loud, that all his teeth wide bare
He laught, and mockt to see him like to swim.
But laught them out, as if his greater pryde
For all her words she drownd with laughter vaine,
That blushing to her laughter gaue more grace,
And laughter to her blushing, as did fall:
But brusting forth in laughter, to her sayd;
That by his grenning laughter mote farre off be rad.
Mother of laughter, and welspring of blisse,
The which her lauish louers to her gaue;
Accourting each her friend with lauish fest:
But of her loue too lauish (litle haue she thancke.)
In daintie delices, and lauish ioyes,
And made there to abound with lauish affluence.
Did decke her, and too lauishly adorne,
So lauishly enricht with natures threasure,
And after spent with pride and lauishnesse,
His fair enchaunted steed, and eke his charmed launce.
And with stiffe force shaking his mortall launce,
And saw it stirre: she left her percing launce,
Whose squire bore after him an heben launce,
Did breake the launce, and let the head abyde:
Beyond his croupe, the length of all her launce,
That fortune all in equall launce doth sway,
Which that same knight, whom by his launce I read,
And eft auentring his steeleheaded launce,
That all his launce in peeces shiuered quite,
Readie to launce her brest, and let out loued life.
Aboue a launces length him forth did beare,
And he eftsoones gan launch his barke forthright.
With which he wont to launch the saluage hart
That launched hath my brest with bleeding smart.
Which loue had launched with his deadly darts,
Through launched, forth her bleeding life does raine,
Forth launched quickly, as she did desire,
From the departing land it launched light,
My feeble brest of late, and launched this wound wyde.
His feeble hart wide launched with loues cruell wound.
And many wide woundes launched through his inner parts.
And launcht his Lordly hart: with death opprest
For since my brest was launcht with louely dart
Which being whylome launcht with louely dart,
My heart was launcht, and learned to haue loued,
As if her breast new launcht with murdrous knife,
The Laurell, meed of mightie Conquerours
But now they laurell braunches bore in hand;
And at his feet their laurell boughes did throw.
In her eternall trompe, with laurell girland cround.
With shady Laurell trees, thence to defend
That in his hand a branch of laurell bore,
Planted with mirtle trees and laurels greene,
Ne would his looser life be tide to law,
Theseus condemned to endlesse slouth by law,
They were by law of that proud Tyrannesse
That his beheast they feared, as tyrans law,
Is not his law, Let euery sinner die:
By righteous sentence of th'Almighties law:
That as a law for euer should endure;
The law of armes, to strike foe vndefide.
Right sowre, & feele the law, the which thou hast defast.
So he now subiect to the victours law,
She hath ordaind this law, which we approue,
Which by her owne law to your lot doth light,
Hath me subiected to loues cruell law:
For all that liues, is subiect to that law:
Gainst natures law, and good behauioure:
But a faire virgin, that in martiall law,
The huge seas vnder her t'obay her seruaunts law.
And eke vnto her lookes a law she made,
And to his law compels all creatures to obay.
According to the custome of their law.
Tyrants that make men subiect to their law,
By law of armes there neede ones right to trie,
My law, and euer to my lore be bound;
There bound t'obay that Amazons proud law,
Chiefely by him, whose life her law doth bynd,
Giue him more labour, and with streighter law,
To breake all bonds of law, and rules of right.
They quite forgot, and scornd all former law;
Nayld to a post, adiudged so by law:
And then the law of Nations gainst her rose,
The law of armes; yet breake it should againe,
So iudgement past, as is by law ordayned
Cryde mercie, to abate the extremitie of law.
Abusde, against all reason and all law,
For were no law in loue, but all that lust,
Vnto his lust, and make his will his law,
And each vnto his lust did make a lawe,
Ne ruld her Realmes with lawes, but pollicie,
T'obserue the sacred lawes of armes, that are assynd.
Emongst wild beasts and woods, from lawes of men exilde.
If euer he transgrest the fatall Stygian lawes.
Of lawes, of iudgements, and of decretals;
Then made he sacred lawes, which some men say
Those yet of her be Mertia[n] lawes both nam'd & thought.
Gan coyne streight lawes to curb their liberty;
Then what prescribed were by lawes of cheualrie.
High Gods beheast, and powre of holy lawes;
And lastly Iustice charged her with breach of lawes.
So now he hath new lawes and orders new
Nor lawes of men, that common weales containe,
And looser thoughts to lawfull bounds withdraw;
Vnlesse the heauens them lift to lawfull soueraintie.
Or did rebell gainst lawfull gouernment;
From raging spoile of lawlesse victors will?
His life he led in lawlesse riotise;
From lawlesse lust by wondrous grace
And to all lawlesse lust encouraged,
All those were lawlesse lustes, corrupt enuies,
Vnto abuse of lawlesse lust was lent,
And lawlesse lust to rule with reasons lore;
Which lawlesse men had formerly fordonne.
Fro me reft mine away by lawlesse might,
Which lawlesse multitude him comming too
Gainst tortious powre and lawlesse regiment,
Purchast through lawlesse powre and tortious wrong
That sought with lawlesse powre him to oppresse,
In execution of her lawlesse doome,
A lawlesse people, Brigants hight of yore,
And made vnfit to serue his lawlesse mindes behest.
Faire lawnds, to take the sunne in season dew;
Both those the lawrell girlonds to the victor dew.
Daunst liuely, and her face did with a Lawrell shade.
Lay forth out of thine euerlasting scryne
Lay now thy deadly Heben bow apart,
And as she lay vpon the durtie ground,
Deliuered it to him, and downe did lay
And comming where the knight in slomber lay,
Then seemed him his Lady by him lay,
Long after lay he musing at her mood,
And on the grasse her daintie limbes did lay
As if her life vpon the wager lay,
He answered nought, but in a traunce still lay,
Like loathsome lazars, by the hedges lay.
And in his bosome secretly there lay
And vnderneath their feet, all scattered lay
Who all that while lay hid in secret shade:
Lay couer'd with inchaunted cloud all day:
Vnto the place, whereas the Paynim lay,
So lay him in her charet, close in night concealed.
His three deformed heads did lay along,
His cunning hand gan to his wounds to lay,
Where in a dongeon deepe huge numbers lay
But most of all, which in the Dongeon lay
Of murdred men which therein strowed lay,
That lay in waite her wrack for to bewaile,
And rusticke horror all a side doe lay,
And all his sences stound, that still he lay full low.
And loue fresh coles vnto her fire did lay:
That headlesse his vnweldy bodie lay,
My dearest Lord, and deepe in dongeon lay,
Ah Loue, lay downe thy bow, the whiles I may respire.
Her daintie limbes full softly down did lay:
And him beside there lay vpon the gras
Vpon her arme a siluer anchor lay,
The man that would not liue, but earst lay at deathes dore.
And comfort those, in point of death which lay;
That forst him lay his heauenly thoughts aside;
Their heauenly notes, and make full many a louely lay.
Where stretcht he lay vpon the sunny side
Faire Goddesse lay that furious fit aside,
All night she watcht, ne once adowne would lay
Out of the well, wherein he drenched lay;
But lay as in a dreame of deepe delight,
So downe he fell, and like an heaped mountaine lay.
In well attuned notes, a ioyous lay,
But when they came, where that dead Dragon lay,
Still as he went, he craftie stales did lay
Into a pleasant dale, that lowly lay
With percing shriekes, and many a dolefull lay;
Of death and labour lay, halfe dead, halfe quicke,
Beside a bubbling fountaine low she lay,
They lay therein those corses tenderly,
And this misseeming discord meekely lay aside.
Whiles in the bush he lay, not yet forgot:
His mightie hands did on the madman lay,
But ouerthrew himselfe vnwares, and lower lay.
To lull him soft a sleepe, that by it lay;
Into the land, that lay them faire before,
The whiles with a loue lay she thus him sweetly charm'd.
Such as he saw, she gan him lay before,
And round about him lay on euery side
All these before the gates of Pluto lay,
That drenched lay full deepe, vnder the Garden side.
Where Guyon lay in traunce, when suddenly
But if some relish of that heauenly lay
Which all along the Southerne sea-coast lay,
And lay strong siege about it far and wide.
Did lay strong siege, and battailous assault,
Against that Castle restlesse siege did lay,
As hurt he had not bene. Thereby there lay
He soone in vomit vp againe doth lay,
The whiles some one did chaunt this louely lay;
Their diuerse notes t'attune vnto his lay,
As lay her iourney, through that perlous Pace,
And her soft arme lay vnderneath his hed,
That doth the charmed Snake in slomber lay:
So dischord oft in Musick makes the sweeter lay.
Lay hidden in the bottome of the pot;
Do lay away, and all wilde beastes do rest,
But standing high aloft, low lay thine eare,
Whiles thus he lay in deadly stonishment,
Was taken with her loue, and by her closely lay.
Ne word did speake, but lay as in a swowne,
That he lay wallowd all in his owne gore.
Comfort to him, that comfortlesse now lay.
With bloud deformed, lay in deadly swownd:
Who al this while lay bleeding out his hart-bloud neare.
Farre in the woods, whiles that he lay in swownd,
Beside the same a dainty place there lay,
In which the birds song many a louely lay
